{"id":"1104.0759","submitter":"Ben Andrews","authors":"Ben Andrews and Paul Bryan","title":"A comparison theorem for the isoperimetric profile under curve\n  shortening flow","comments":"32 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We prove a comparison theorem for the isoperimetric profiles of simple closed\ncurves evolving by the normalized curve shortening flow: If the isoperimetric\nprofile of the region enclosed by the initial curve is greater than that of\nsome `model' convex region with exactly four vertices and with reflection\nsymmetry in both axes, then the inequality remains true for the isoperimetric\nprofiles of the evolved regions. We apply this using the Angenent solution as\nthe model region to deduce sharp time-dependent upper bounds on curvature for\narbitrary embedded closed curves evolving by the normalized curve shortening\nflow. A slightly different comparison also gives lower bounds on curvature, and\nthe result is a simple and direct proof of Grayson's theorem without use of any\nblowup or compactness arguments, Harnack estimates, or classification of\nself-similar solutions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 5 Apr 2011 08:01:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-03-19"}
